04505nam a2200697Ia 9780801455162DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979723451  a97808014551627 a10.7591/97808014551622doi  a(DE-B1597)478222  a(OCoLC)886740418  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aUG447.8b.S583 2016 7aPOL0120002bisacsh04a358.3842231 aSmith, Frank L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAmerican Biodefense :bHow Dangerous Ideas about Biological Weapons Shape National Security /cFrank L. Smith. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (204 p.) :b1 halftone, 1 table, 1 chart  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in Security Affairs00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAcronyms -- tAmerican Biodefense, from Boston to Baghdad -- t1. Science and Technology for National Security -- t2. Stereotypical Neglect of Military Research, Development, and Acquisition for Biodefense -- t3. Fatal Assumptions -- t4. An Unlikely Sponsor? -- tBiodefense and Beyond -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBiological weapons have threatened U.S. national security since at least World War II. Historically, however, the U.S. military has neglected research, development, acquisition, and doctrine for biodefense. Following September 11 and the anthrax letters of 2001, the United States started spending billions of dollars per year on medical countermeasures and biological detection systems. But most of this funding now comes from the Department of Health and Human Services rather than the Department of Defense. Why has the U.S. military neglected biodefense and allowed civilian organizations to take the lead in defending the country against biological attacks? In American Biodefense, Frank L. Smith III addresses this puzzling and largely untold story about science, technology, and national security.Smith argues that organizational frames and stereotypes have caused both military neglect and the rise of civilian biodefense. In the armed services, influential ideas about kinetic warfare have undermined defense against biological warfare. The influence of these ideas on science and technology challenges the conventional wisdom that national security policy is driven by threats or bureaucratic interests. Given the ideas at work inside the U.S. military, Smith explains how the lessons learned from biodefense can help solve other important problems that range from radiation weapons to cyber attacks.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aBiological warfarezUnited StatesxSafety measures. 0aBiosecurityzUnited States. 0aCivil defensezUnited States. 0aNational securityzUnited States. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aU.S. History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh  abioterrorism, biological warfare, weapons of mass destruction, kinetic warfare.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145516240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801455162423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801455162/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles